                <p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: justify;"><span>Normal =
Distribution is the most common or normal form of distribution of Random Va=
riables</span><b><strong>,</strong></b><span> hence the name "normal distri=
bution." It is also called the </span><b><strong>Gaussian Distribution</str=
ong></b><span> in Statistics or Probability. We use this distribution to re=
present a large number of random variables. It serves as a foundation for s=
tatistics and probability theory. </span></p><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-a=
lign: justify;"><span>It also describes many natural phenomena, forms the b=
asis of the </span><a href=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/maths/central-l=
imit-theorem/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener"><span>Central Limit Theor=
em</span></a><span>, and supports numerous statistical methods.</span></p><=
blockquote><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: justify;"><b><strong>Normal =
distribution</strong></b><span> is a continuous probability distribution th=
at is symmetric about the mean, depicting that data near the mean are more =
frequent in occurrence than data far from the mean.</span></p></blockquote>=
<figure class=3D"image"><img src=3D"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-cont=
ent/uploads/20250606125317822107/a_normal_distribution1.webp" alt=3D"a_norm=
al_distribution1" width=3D"619" height=3D"400"><figcaption>Fig 1: Normal Di=
stribution</figcaption></figure><blockquote><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>As shown i=
n Fig 1, the distribution is symmetric about its center, which is the mean =
(0 in this case). This symmetry means that events equidistant from the mean=
 have equal probabilities. The density is highest near the mean, resulting =
in lower probabilities for values farther away from it.</span></p></blockqu=
ote><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>We define Normal Distribution as the probability d=
ensity function of any continuous random variable for any given system. Now=
 for defining Normal Distribution suppose we take f(x) as the probability d=
ensity function for any random variable X. </span></p><ul><li value=3D"1"><=
span>The area under the curve of a normal distribution is always 1.</span><=
/li><li value=3D"2"><span>The curve traced by the upper values of the Norma=
l Distribution is in the shape of a Bell, hence Normal Distribution is also=
 called the "</span><b><strong>Bell Curve"</strong></b><span>.</span></li><=
/ul><h2 id=3D"normal-distribution-formula" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>=
Normal Distribution Formula</span></h2><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>The formula for=
 the probability density function of the Normal Distribution (Gaussian Dist=
ribution) is added below:</span></p><figure class=3D"image"><img src=3D"htt=
ps://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250724124157186985/Probab=
ility-Density-for-Normal-Distribution-1.png" alt=3D"Probability-Density-for=
-Normal-Distribution-1" width=3D"780" height=3D"338" loading=3D"lazy"><figc=
aption>Probability Density Formula for Normal Distribution</figcaption></fi=
gure><blockquote><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>where,</span></p><ul><li value=3D"1">=
<span>x is </span><a href=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/random-variable/=
" rel=3D"noopener"><b><strong>Random Variable</strong></b></a></li><li valu=
e=3D"2"><span>=CE=BC is </span><a href=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/mat=
hs/what-is-mean/" rel=3D"noopener"><b><strong>Mean</strong></b></a></li><li=
 value=3D"3"><span>=CF=83 is </span><a href=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.or=
g/maths/standard-deviation-formula/" rel=3D"noopener"><b><strong>Standard D=
eviation</strong></b></a></li></ul></blockquote><h2 id=3D"key-features-of-n=
ormal-distribution" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>Normal Distribution Cha=
racteristics</span></h2><ul><li value=3D"1"><b><strong>Symmetry:</strong></=
b><span> The normal distribution is symmetric around its mean. This means t=
he left side of the distribution mirrors the right side.</span></li><li val=
ue=3D"2"><b><strong>Mean, Median, and Mode:</strong></b><span> In a normal =
distribution, the mean, median, and mode are all equal and located at the c=
enter of the distribution.</span></li><li value=3D"3"><b><strong>Bell-shape=
d Curve:</strong></b><span> The curve is bell-shaped, indicating that most =
of the observations cluster around the central peak and the probabilities f=
or values further away from the mean taper off equally in both directions.<=
/span></li><li value=3D"4"><b><strong>Standard Deviation:</strong></b><span=
> The spread of the distribution is determined by the standard deviation. A=
bout 68% of the data falls within one standard deviation of the mean, 95% w=
ithin two standard deviations, and 99.7% within three standard deviations.<=
/span></li></ul><h2 id=3D"normal-distribution-examples" style=3D"text-align=
:left"><span>Normal Distribution Examples</span></h2><p dir=3D"ltr" style=
=3D"text-align: justify;"><span>We can draw a Normal Distribution for vario=
us types of data that include,</span></p><div id=3D"GFG_AD_Desktop_InConten=
t_ATF_728x280" style=3D"text-align: center; margin: 10px 0px;"></div><ul><l=
i value=3D"1"><span>Distribution of Height of People.</span></li><li value=
=3D"2"><span>Distribution of Errors in any Measurement.</span></li><li valu=
e=3D"3"><span>Distribution of Blood Pressure of any Patient, etc.</span></l=
i></ul><h2 id=3D"normal-distribution-curve" style=3D"text-align:left"><span=
>Normal Distribution Curve</span></h2><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: s=
tart;"><span>In a&nbsp;</span><b><strong>Normal Distribution</strong></b><s=
pan>, a&nbsp;</span><b><strong>random variable</strong></b><span>&nbsp;(</s=
pan><i><em class=3D"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic">X</em></i><span>) is a nume=
rical outcome of a process that follows this distribution. The values of&nb=
sp;</span><i><em class=3D"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic">X</em></i><span>&nbsp=
;are not fixed but instead vary according to the distribution=E2=80=99s pro=
perties, where:</span></p><ul><li value=3D"1"><span>The variable is&nbsp;</=
span><b><strong>continuous</strong></b><span>&nbsp;(can take any real value=
 within a range).</span></li><li value=3D"2"><span>The distribution is defi=
ned by its&nbsp;</span><b><strong>mean (=CE=BC) -</strong></b><span> the pe=
ak of the curve&nbsp;and&nbsp;</span><b><strong>standard deviation (=CF=83)=
</strong></b><span> - which controls the spread of the curve.</span></li></=
ul><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: start;"><span>The&nbsp;</span><b><st=
rong>Normal Distribution Curve</strong></b><span>&nbsp;(also called the&nbs=
p;</span><b><strong>Bell Curve</strong></b><span>&nbsp;or&nbsp;</span><b><s=
trong>Gaussian Curve</strong></b><span>) is the graphical representation of=
 this distribution, showing:</span></p><ol><li value=3D"1"><b><strong>Symme=
try</strong></b><span>&nbsp;around the mean (=CE=BC).</span></li><li value=
=3D"2"><b><strong>68-95-99.7% Rule</strong></b><span>&nbsp;(Empirical Rule)=
 for data spread.</span></li><li value=3D"3"><b><strong>Asymptotic tails</s=
trong></b><span>&nbsp;(the curve never touches the x-axis but extends infin=
itely).</span></li></ol><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: start;"><span>U=
nlike some distributions, the normal distribution is&nbsp;not strictly "bou=
nd" to a finite range=E2=80=94it theoretically spans from&nbsp;</span><b><s=
trong>=E2=88=92=E2=88=9E to +=E2=88=9E</strong></b><span>, though extreme v=
alues are highly improbable.</span></p><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>An example of t=
he random variable is, suppose we take a </span><b><strong>distribution of =
the height of students in a class, then the random variable can take any va=
lue in this</strong></b><span> </span><b><strong>case, but is bound by a bo=
undary of 2 ft to 6 ft, as it is generally forced physically.</strong></b><=
/p><h2 id=3D"normal-distribution-standard-deviation" style=3D"text-align:le=
ft"><span>Standard Deviation of Normal Distribution</span></h2><p dir=3D"lt=
r" style=3D"text-align: justify;"><span>The mean of any data spread out as =
a graph helps us to find the line of symmetry of the graph. Standard Deviat=
ion tells us how far the data is spread out from the mean value on either s=
ide. </span></p><div id=3D"GFG_AD_Incontent_2" style=3D"text-align: center;=
 margin: 10px 0px;"></div><ul><li value=3D"1"><span>For smaller values of t=
he standard deviation, the values in the graph come closer and the graph be=
comes narrower. </span></li><li value=3D"2"><span>For higher values of the =
standard deviation, the values in the graph are dispersed more, and the gra=
ph becomes wider.</span></li></ul><h3 id=3D"empirical-rule-of-standard-devi=
ation" style=3D"text-align:left"><b><strong>Empirical Rule of Standard Devi=
ation</strong></b></h3><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: justify;"><span>=
Generally, the normal distribution has a positive standard deviation, and t=
he standard deviation divides the area of the normal curve into smaller par=
ts, and each part defines the percentage of data that falls into a specific=
 region. This is called the Empirical Rule of Standard Deviation in Normal =
Distribution.</span></p><blockquote><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: jus=
tify;"><b><strong>Empirical Rule states that,</strong></b></p><ul><li value=
=3D"1"><span>68% of the data approximately fall within one standard deviati=
on of the mean, i.e. it falls between {</span><b><strong>Mean - One Standar=
d Deviation, and Mean + One Standard Deviation</strong></b><span>}</span></=
li><li value=3D"2"><span>95% of the data approximately fall within two stan=
dard deviations of the mean, i.e. it falls between {</span><b><strong>Mean =
- Two Standard Deviation, and Mean + Two Standard Deviation</strong></b><sp=
an>}</span></li><li value=3D"3"><span>99.7% of the data approximately fall =
within a third standard deviation of the mean, i.e. it falls between {</spa=
n><b><strong>Mean - Third Standard Deviation, and Mean + Third Standard Dev=
iation</strong></b><span>}</span></li></ul></blockquote><p dir=3D"ltr" styl=
e=3D"text-align: justify;"><img src=3D"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-c=
ontent/uploads/20230901155813/Probability-Distribution-Curve.png" alt=3D"No=
rmal Distribution Curve" width=3D"531" height=3D"inherit" loading=3D"lazy">=
</p><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: justify;"><span>Studying </span><b>=
<strong>the graph, it is clear that using the Empirical Rule, we distribute=
 data broadly in three parts. Thus, the empirical rule is also called the "=
68 =E2=80=93 95 =E2=80=93 99.7" rule. The curve is perfectly symmetric arou=
nd the mean (</strong></b><span>=CE=BC), which is located at the center and=
 marks the highest point of the curve. This mean represents the average val=
ue of the datasheet. This distribution is commonly used in real-world stati=
stics to represent things like test scores, height, and measurement errors,=
 where most of the values tend to cluster around the average, and extreme v=
alues are less common.</span></p><h2 id=3D"normal-distribution-table" style=
